data.content:
## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement — aborting a thread that exceeds a time limit.

**Why it breaks:** `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. There is no way to forcibly kill a managed thread.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Task.Run moves the work to the thread pool
        var task = Task.Run(work);

        try
        {
            // WaitAsync throws TimeoutException if the task doesn't
            // complete within the deadline (.NET 6+ API)
            return task.WaitAsync(timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Preferred async version

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(cancellationToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                             .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // The timeout fired, not the caller's token
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Cooperative cancellation only works if `work` checks the token. If it's a tight CPU loop or blocking I/O that ignores the token, the task keeps running in the background after the timeout fires. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` is `IDisposable` — always wrap in `using`. Leaking it leaks internal timers. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when` guard above distinguishes timeout from caller cancellation. Without it you'd mask real cancellations. |
| **Uncooperative code** | If `work` calls a third-party API that can't accept a `CancellationToken`, the work will finish eventually even after you've thrown `TimeoutException`. The only true kill mechanism is `Process.Kill` on a child process. |

### Making the work cooperate (if you control it)

```csharp
// Pass the token into the work so it can actually stop
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example — token is checked inside the loop
executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return items.Count;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### What was removed and why

| .NET Framework API | Status in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | Never thrown | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
